// Vitest Snapshot v1, https://vitest.dev/guide/snapshot.html

exports[`buildAuditCodebasePrompt > renders project section and references codebase file path 1`] = `
"You are part of a tool that helps the user build a project incrementally.
An **audit of existing code** is in progress — DO NOT implement any new features,
do not refactor anything, do not modify the project's source code. Your only output
is the file \`.mini/codebase.md\`.

# Project
# Můj projekt
Stavím nástroj X pro Y.

# Your task
Go through the existing code in the current directory and build (or update) an
overview of the project for later use by the orchestrator in the file \`.mini/codebase.md\`.
This file serves **you yourself in later sessions** (\`do\`/\`plan\`/\`next\`) as a quick
overview — instead of repeatedly walking through \`src/\` you can read this summary.
The tone matches that: paths, module names, technologies, short bullet points.
No long prose for humans.

## If \`.mini/codebase.md\` already exists
1. **Your very first action** must be \`Read\` on \`.mini/codebase.md\` — go through
   the existing content so you know what is already described and what the user
   added by hand.
2. **DO NOT REWRITE the whole file.** Use \`Edit\`, not \`Write\`. Only fix sections
   that do not match the real state of the code.
3. The user's manual notes (comments, additions, sections beyond the template) **must
   be preserved** — even if they look redundant at first glance. When in doubt,
   leave them be.

## If \`.mini/codebase.md\` does not exist
Create it via \`Write\` with the following structure (section names are fixed;
you may leave a section empty if there is nothing to write):

\`\`\`
# {project name} — code overview

## Overview
(2-4 sentences: what the project does technically — runtime, input/output, main use case)

## Directory structure
(as a tree or bullets: top-level directories and their roles)

## Key modules
(bullets: path + one-sentence description. Example: \`src/cli.ts\` — entrypoint, parses arguments.)

## Technologies
(bullets: language, framework, libraries, build tooling, test runner — whatever is relevant)
\`\`\`

## How to proceed
- Start from \`package.json\` / \`pyproject.toml\` / equivalent — from that you learn the
  language, dependencies and entrypoints.
- Then go through the top-level directories (\`Glob\`, \`LS\`) and the main source files (\`Read\`).
- Stick to facts. Do not guess a module's purpose when it is unclear from the code —
  rather leave it out of \`Key modules\` or honestly write "(unidentified)".
- Ignore files like \`node_modules/\`, \`dist/\`, \`.git/\`, \`coverage/\` and similar build
  artifacts.

# You may use
\`Read\`, \`Grep\`, \`Glob\`, \`LS\` for reading, \`Write\` to create a new
\`.mini/codebase.md\`, and \`Edit\` for incremental updates. You don't need any other tools.
"
`;
